All API endpoints  are then live at http://localhost:4010.  Track 3 must consume  this mock server  -  do 
not invent your own contract. Track 1 and Track 2 participants  may also use it to test their 
implementations  against the shared OpenAPI  contract. 
 
3. Shared Data Contract  -  Canonical Trade Schema 
All three tracks implement  or consume  this exact schema.  Any deviation  breaks interoperability  scoring. 
Field names, types, and enum values are not negotiable. 
 
{   tradeId:         uuid v4,   userId:          uuid v4,   asset:           string,                        // e.g. 'AAPL', 'BTC/USD'   assetClass:      equity | crypto | forex,   direction:       long | short,   entryPrice:      decimal(18,8),   exitPrice:       decimal(18,8) | null,   quantity:        decimal(18,8),   entryAt:         ISO-8601 UTC,   exitAt:          ISO-8601 UTC | null,   status:          open | closed | cancelled,   planAdherence:   integer 1-5 | null,           // user self-rating at close   emotionalState:  calm | anxious | greedy | fearful | neutral | null,   entryRationale:  string <= 500 chars | null,   sessionId:       uuid v4                       // groups trades in one session } 
 
  
TRACK 1   System of Record   Backend Engineering 
Problem Statement 
Build a real-time trade journal engine  with behavioral  analytics  -  defined contracts, proven  throughput. 
NevUp's  core stores every trade with its full psychological  context: not just P&L, but the emotional 
state, entry rationale, and plan adherence for each decision. You will build the write path, the async 
analytics pipeline,  and the read API from scratch. The system must be provably  correct under load, 
multi-tenant  by default, and expose a contract that the System of AI Engine and System of Engagement 
tracks can depend on without negotiation. 
 
Seed Data 
File: nevup_seed_dataset.csv  -  388 trades, 10 traders,  52 sessions.  Load this into your database 
on container  startup via a migration or seed script. The GET /users/:id/metrics  endpoint must return 
queryable  results against this dataset  from the moment reviewers  run docker compose up. 
 
Behavioral Metrics  -  Compute All Five 
These five metrics must be computed  asynchronously  outside the write path for every closed trade. 
Their definitions are deterministic   -  two independent  implementations  must produce  identical outputs 
from the same input. 
 
# Metric Definition 
1 Plan Adherence 
Score 
Rolling 10-trade average  of planAdherence  ratings per user. 
Queryable  via the read API. 
2 Revenge Trade 
Flag 
If a trade opens within 90 seconds of a losing close AND 
emotionalState  is anxious or fearful, tag that trade revengeFlag = 
true. 
3 Session Tilt Index Ratio of (loss-following  trades / total trades)  in the current 
sessionId.  Updated on each close event. 
4 Win Rate by 
Emotional  State 
For each emotionalState  value, maintain a per-user  running 
win/loss count. Must be queryable via the read API with date range 
filtering. 
5 Overtrading 
Detector 
If a user opens more than 10 trades in any 30-minute  sliding 
window, emit an overtrading  event onto the event bus. Must not 
block the write path. 
 
Hard Requirements 
# Requirement Detail 
1 Idempotent  Write 
API 
POST /trades must be idempotent  on tradeId. Duplicate 
submissions  must return HTTP 200 with the existing record  -  not 
500 or 409. Prove this in automated tests. 
